    title: "Canary Releases and Safe Deployment with Triton",
    content: "Canary deployment is the safest strategy for rolling out new model versions to production. Instead of replacing the current model entirely, the new version is deployed alongside it and receives a small percentage of traffic. If the new version performs well during the canary window, traffic is gradually shifted until it handles 100 percent. If it regresses, traffic is instantly reverted to the old version.\n\nTriton Inference Server supports canary deployments natively through its version policy. By configuring version_policy with latest and num_versions set to 2, Triton loads both the current and new model versions simultaneously. The server assigns each version a distinct endpoint, allowing external traffic management to control the split.\n\nThe traffic splitting itself is typically managed by a Kubernetes Ingress controller or service mesh like Istio. The initial split might route 10 percent of requests to the new version and 90 percent to the current version. Monitoring runs for a defined canary window, typically 30 minutes to several hours depending on traffic volume.\n\nThe critical decision metric during the canary window is whether the error rate and P99 latency stay within baseline thresholds. If the new version's error rate is comparable to or better than the old version, and its latency remains within the SLA budget, the canary is promoted. If either metric degrades beyond the threshold, an automatic rollback routes all traffic back to the old version.\n\nTriton's hot model reloading capability enables version updates without downtime. The REST API endpoint at /v2/repository/models/{model}/load triggers Triton to scan the model repository for new versions and load them into GPU memory while continuing to serve existing versions. This means the deployment pipeline can upload a new model version to the repository, trigger a reload, and begin the canary split without any service interruption.\n\nFor safety-critical drone applications, canary deployments provide an essential safety net. Even if the evaluation threshold in CI is set correctly, real-world production traffic may differ from the validation set in ways that only become apparent under actual operational conditions. The canary window catches these production-specific regressions before they affect the entire fleet.",
