    title: "Common Pitfalls and Edge Cases in ML CI/CD",
    content: "The most dangerous pitfall in ML CI/CD is the assumption that passing tests equals model quality. A model training pipeline can be technically correct, producing valid outputs and passing all unit tests, while still producing a significantly worse model due to subtle data issues, hyperparameter drift, or hardware differences between training and serving environments.\n\nGPU non-determinism is a common source of confusion. Even with the same code, data, and random seed, training on different GPU architectures can produce slightly different models due to floating-point operation ordering differences. CI pipelines should account for this by using relative accuracy thresholds rather than expecting bitwise identical results.\n\nData leakage between training and validation splits is another insidious problem. If the CI pipeline creates train-test splits dynamically rather than using fixed, versioned splits managed by DVC, there is a risk of data contamination where the same images appear in both sets, artificially inflating evaluation metrics.\n\nONNX export compatibility issues frequently cause CI failures. A model that trains successfully in PyTorch may fail to export to ONNX if it uses dynamic control flow, custom operators, or unsupported layer types. The CI pipeline should include an explicit ONNX export and validation step that catches these issues before they reach the deployment stage.\n\nSecret management for MLflow tracking server credentials, DVC remote storage authentication, and Triton server access must be handled through GitHub Actions secrets, never hardcoded in workflow files. For self-hosted runners, credential rotation and access control are the runner operator's responsibility.\n\nStorage costs can escalate rapidly if every CI run stores large model artifacts. Implementing artifact retention policies that keep only the most recent N artifacts per branch, plus all artifacts for tagged releases, prevents storage bloat while maintaining traceability for production deployments.\n\nThe interaction between DVC caching and CI runner storage deserves attention. If self-hosted runners share a DVC cache directory, subsequent runs on the same machine can skip data downloads. However, cache invalidation and concurrent access patterns must be carefully managed to avoid corrupted caches.",
