    title: "Advanced Considerations: Model Drift, Active Learning, and Continuous Training",
    content: "The ML CI/CD pipeline does not end at deployment. Production monitoring feeds back into the training pipeline through drift detection and active learning loops. When Evidently AI detects significant data drift in the production inference stream, it can automatically trigger a retraining pipeline by creating a new GitHub Actions workflow dispatch event.\n\nActive learning integrates with CI/CD by automating the sample selection and labeling request process. When the production model encounters inputs where its confidence falls below a threshold, those inputs are flagged for human annotation. Once annotated, they are added to the training dataset, DVC tracks the new version, and the CI pipeline automatically retrains and evaluates the updated model.\n\nModel drift refers specifically to when incoming production data distribution diverges from training data. This triggers uncertainty sampling to select new labels from the shifted distribution. The CI pipeline processes this new labeled data, validates it through Great Expectations, retrains the model, evaluates against the accuracy threshold, and deploys through the canary process.\n\nContinuous Delivery versus Continuous Deployment represents a critical architectural decision. Continuous Delivery requires human approval before production deployment, meaning the pipeline stages everything in the MLflow registry as Staging and waits for a human to promote to Production. Continuous Deployment is fully automated, promoting passing models directly. For safety-critical drone applications, Continuous Delivery with human approval gates is generally preferred.\n\nThe model promotion workflow in MLflow follows a standard progression: a new model enters as None, gets promoted to Staging after passing CI evaluation, undergoes canary testing, and is promoted to Production after successful canary validation. The previous Production model is transitioned to Archived, maintaining it as a rollback target.\n\nEnd-to-end pipeline orchestration tools like Kubeflow Pipelines or Airflow can manage the complete lifecycle from data ingestion through model serving. These tools provide DAG-based workflow definitions, artifact lineage tracking, and conditional branching that enables sophisticated automation patterns like automatic rollback when post-deployment metrics degrade.",
